  "output": "No test suite to worry about breaking. Here's the analysis.\n\n## Scope note\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (httpx + SQLite + asyncio), not a web app — there's no React, no frontend at all. I'm skipping that category and mapping the others onto Python-equivalents: SQLite round-trips instead of ORM N+1, per-item regex/hash recomputation instead of re-renders.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-73` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, it does a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With 114 sources in `sources.yaml` (several defaulting to 30-40 pages of pagination), a single run can push thousands of round-trips to SQLite.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):          # stay under SQLite's ~999 var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in cur.execute(q, chunk))\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ..., :now, :now)\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(N) round-trips into O(N/500 + 3).\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(include)`/`_compile(exclude)` **inside that per-job call** — the same keyword list gets `re.compile`'d fresh for every single listing.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or ())\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or ())\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n`match` now takes pre-compiled pattern lists. This is called nowhere else (`git grep` confirms `filter_jobs` is the only caller), so it's a safe signature change. This is your single highest-impact fix — it runs on every job, every run.\n\n## 3. Memory bloat — `fetchers.py` (`raw=j` on 7 of 15 parsers)\n\n`Job.raw` is popped in `to_row()` before it ever reaches SQLite (`models.py:73`), and a repo-wide grep shows nothing else reads `.raw`. Yet `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, and `parse_workable` all do `raw=j` — storing the **entire** source payload (Lever/Ashby postings include full description HTML) per job, held live in the `jobs` list through fetch → filter → diff. The newer bespoke fetchers (Google, D.E. Shaw, Two Sigma, Optiver, Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon) already learned this and store a 1-2 key dict instead — that's the pattern to copy:\n\n```python\n# fetchers.py:64-73, and similarly for lever/ashby/smartrecruiters/recruitee/workable\nout.append(Job(\n    ...,\n    raw={\"id\": str(j[\"id\"])},   # instead of raw=j\n))\n```\nSince it's write-only dead weight, you could also just drop the field from `Job` entirely — but keeping a tiny `{\"id\": ...}` preserves the debugging value the newer fetchers use it for.\n\n## 4. Redundant computation — `store.py` (`content_hash` computed twice)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a `@property` (sha256 over 4 fields), recomputed on every access. In `diff()`, a changed job hits it once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_update`'s `job.to_row()`. Cheap per-call, but easy to avoid — compute once and pass it through:\n\n```python\nh = job.content_hash\nif h != existing_hash:\n    row = {**job.to_row(with_hash=h), ...}\n```\nLow priority given sha256 on a short string is microseconds, but free to fix alongside the batching change in #1.\n\n## 5. Minor — blocking I/O inside the async pipeline (`pipeline.py:42-44`, `notify.py`)\n\n`store.diff()` and `dispatch()` run synchronously inside `async def run()`, and `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` use blocking `httpx.post` (not `httpx.AsyncClient`), while `notify_email` uses blocking `smtplib`. Today this is harmless — `fetch_all` has already finished, so nothing else is waiting on the event loop — but if notify or store logic ever gets called while other coroutines are in flight, these calls will stall the loop. Not worth restructuring now; just don't reuse `dispatch()`/`Store` calls inside a genuinely concurrent section without converting them to async.\n\n## What's *not* an issue here\n\n- `fetch_all` correctly shares one `httpx.AsyncClient` across all 114 sources with a semaphore-bounded concurrency (`fetchers.py:767-788`) — no per-request client churn.\n- Per-source pagination loops (Two Sigma, Optiver, Google, Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon) all dedupe with a `seen` set and stop on the first empty/stale page — no unbounded pagination.\n- `agent.py`'s ATS-normalization regexes (`_ATS_RULES`) are already compiled once at module scope, not per-call.\n\nWant me to apply fixes #1 and #2 (the two with real measurable impact)?\n",
